<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="56" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1267,1508]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1268,1292]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[324,516,1268,1292]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ashleyi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[324,516,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Epimeria ashleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[525,617,1268,1292]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[525,617,1268,1292]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[903,1002,1268,1292]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horsti">
<emphasis box="[903,1002,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">E. horsti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a pronounced dorsal carina starting on the sixth pereonite. 
<taxonomicName box="[503,680,1304,1328]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="horsti">
<emphasis box="[503,680,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Epimeria horsti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, lacks the double dorsal carinae, lacks the lateral projections on pereonites 
<number box="[369,383,1339,1363]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" value="6.0">6</number>
and 
<number box="[438,454,1340,1363]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" value="7.0">7</number>
, its coxa 
<number box="[559,573,1339,1363]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" value="4.0">4</number>
is smaller and coxa 
<number box="[802,816,1339,1363]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" value="5.0">5</number>
more laterally pointed than in 
<taxonomicName box="[1162,1272,1340,1364]" class="Malacostraca" family="Epimeriidae" genus="Epimeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="7" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ashleyi">
<emphasis box="[1162,1272,1340,1364]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">E. ashleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1375,1400]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">Biology.</emphasis>
The stomach contents of the 
<typeStatus box="[634,731,1377,1401]" pageId="7" pageNumber="56">paratype</typeStatus>
did not reveal distinct food items. Some muscle and collagen fibres were clearly visible, as were what appeared to be plant tissues. The plant material, confirmed by experts as not algal, most likely came from sunken wood.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
